{"title_page": "Everything Bad Is Good for You", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = Everything Bad Is Good for You\n| image         = Everything Bad Cover.JPG\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Everything Bad Is Good for You Cover\n| author        = [[Steven Johnson (author)|Steven Johnson]]\n| cover_artist  = Jamie Keenan\n| country       = \n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| subject       = [[Popular culture]], [[Cultural studies]]\n| publisher     = [[Riverhead Books|Riverhead]]\n| pub_date      = May 2005\n| pages         = 272\n| isbn          = 978-1-59448-194-9\n| congress= HM621 .J64 2006\n| oclc= 69992179\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''Everything Bad Is Good for You: How Today's Popular Culture Is Actually Making Us Smarter''''' is a non-fiction book written by [[Steven Johnson (author)|Steven Johnson]]. Published in 2005, it is based upon Johnson's theory that [[popular culture]] \u2013 in particular [[television program]]s and [[video games]] \u2013 has grown more complex and demanding over time and is making society as a whole more intelligent. The book's claims, especially related to the proposed benefits of television, drew media attention.<ref>{{cite news | title = Fun and Computer Games Make for Smarter Children | date = 4 June 2005 | first = Jim | last = McClellan | newspaper = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]]}}</ref> It received mixed critical reviews.\n\nJohnson states that he aims to persuade readers of \"two things:\n#By almost all the standards we use to measure reading\u2019s cognitive benefits \u2014 attention, memory, following threads, and so on \u2014 the nonliterary popular culture has been steadily growing more challenging over the past thirty years.\n#Increasingly, the nonliterary popular culture is honing ''different'' mental skills that are just as important as the ones exercised by reading books.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title = Everything Bad is Good For You: How Today's Popular Culture is Actually Making Us Smarter|last = Johnson|first = Steven|publisher = Riverhead|year = 2005|isbn = 978-1-59448-194-9|location = |pages = |url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/everythingbadisg00john_0}}</ref>\n\n==Key concepts==\nJohnson challenges the precept that pop culture is deteriorating as a result of new media platforms. He derives the term ''Sleeper Curve'' from the [[Woody Allen]] film ''[[Sleeper (1973 film)|Sleeper]]'', where \"scientists from 2173 are astounded that twentieth-century society failed to grasp the nutritional merits of cream pies and hot fudge\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|last = Johnson|first = Steven|authorlink = |editor = |title = Everything Bad is Good for You|year = 2005|url = https://archive.org/details/everythingbadisg00john_0|format = |accessdate = |edition = |series = |date = |publisher = Riverhead|location = |language = |isbn = 978-1-59448-194-9|oclc = |doi = |id = |pages = |chapter = |chapterurl = |quote = |url-access = registration}}</ref>{{Rp|xvi}} He uses this to argue against contemporary perception of the deteriorating standards of pop culture, although Johnson is quick to point out that by no means does the Sleeper Curve imply that popular culture has become superior to traditional culture.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|132}} Johnson utilizes the following media sources to support his argument:\n\n=== Video games ===\nHe argues that the appeal of video games is not through their (possibly violent or sexual) content, but rather through the fact that the \"structure\" of the [[video games]] uniquely invites exploration and stimulates the [[Reward center of the brain|reward centers of the brain]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|34, 38}} In pointing out arguments for the support of video games, Johnson sheds light on how kids can be more involved in games than in class, but this involvement can teach them that which could be taught in class.<ref name=\":1\" /> To substantiate this argument, he discusses how games and other virtual worlds have immediate rewards, whereas in reality, rewards can take a while to obtain. Johnson states \u201cif you create a  system where rewards are both clearly defined and achieved by exploring an environment, you\u2019ll find human brains drawn to those systems, even if they\u2019re made up of virtual characters and simulated sidewalks. It\u2019s not the subject matter of these games that attracts\u2026it\u2019s the reward system\u201d.<ref name=\":1\" /> Finally, he argues for the support of video games because they also require one to make decisions, whereas books and other forms of art may conjure up imagination and emotions but don't require decision-making.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nJohnson acknowledges that although the video game industry is growing, the literature on the subject is limited at best. Johnson offers several sources for information on [[Game studies|ludology]]; [http://www.ludology.org/ Ludology.org] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20120919061609/http://seriousgames.org/ seriousgames.org] as well as the books ''Got Game'' by John Beck and Mitchell Wade and ''The Play Ethic'' by [[Pat Kane]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|224\u2013225}}\n\n=== Television and film ===\nJohnson admits that television and film demand less decision-making skills than video games, but also says that the benefits from reading (attention, patience, retention, the parsing of narrative threads, etc.) are making a rise in television and film as well, despite its lack of translating letters to meaning or activating the imagination in quite the same way that books do.<ref name=\":1\" /> He discusses three principles of television and film: \"multiple threading,\" \"flashing arrow,\" and \"social networks.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> \"Multiple threading\", according to Johnson, is marrying complex narrative structure to complex subject matter with multiple plots and subplots (for example, he states that shows like ''ER'' & ''24'' have up to 10 threads per episode).<ref name=\":1\" /> He states that a \"Flashing Arrow\" is a kind of narrative signpost purposely planted to help the audience keep track of what's going on, but there has been an increasing lack of arrows over the years both, and this lack of arrows is used to draw on intricate plotlines and obscure references.<ref name=\":1\" /> Finally, he states that \"reality shows demand that we track multiple relationships, since the action of these shows revolves around the shifting feuds and alliances between more than a dozen individuals\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> Johnson says this activates social intelligence, defining it as \u201cour ability to monitor and recall many distinct vectors of interaction in the population around us\u201d and, thus, watchers shall be able to better understand social networks.<ref name=\":1\" /> He asserts that television is a \"brilliant medium\" for determining how skilled people are at understanding interpersonal connections, or their [[Autism-spectrum quotient|Autism Quotient]] (the higher a person's emotional intelligence, the lower their \"AQ\"),<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|98\u201399}} and that [[Reality television|reality shows]] in particular realistically display the complexity of \"[[social network]] maps\" in human relations, where a group of people have complex and intertwined engagement.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|108}}\n\nEarlier television, Johnson says, simplified narrative and human relationships, while modern trends not only in reality shows but in \"multiple [[Narrative thread|threading]]\" in scripted programs such as ''[[The Sopranos]]'' improve the audience's cognitive skills.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|67, 72}} He suggests too that modern television and films have reduced the number of \"[[flashing arrow]]s\", narrative clues to help the audience understand the plot, and require audiences to do more cognitive work paying attention to background detail and information if they wish to follow what they are viewing.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|73\u201374, 77\u201378}}\n\nLater in the book, he mentions that these features of television are also prevalent in film, too.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== The internet ===\nJohnson argues that the internet \u201chas challenged our minds in three fundamental and related ways: by being participatory, by forcing users to learn new interfaces, and by creating new channels for social interaction.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> He uses blogs and utilizing Google to learn things as examples of participation.<ref name=\":1\" /> He declares that \u201caccelerating pace of new platforms and software applications forces users to probe and master new environments\u201d such as \u201clearning the tricks of a new e-mail client, configuring the video chat software properly, getting your bearings after installing a new operating system.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> Additionally, he points out that \u201cin the past few years [the Web has] been [a tool] for augmenting social connection\u201d naming \u201conline personals, social and business network sites such as Friendster, the meetup.com service so central to the political organization of the 2004 campaign.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Overall, he presents evidence to buttress the Internet's benefits.\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe book has received mixed critical reviews. In one ''[[The New York Times]]'' review, [[Janet Maslin]] was primarily negative, dismissing the book's \"facile argument\" and sparsity of hard evidence and claiming that \"The reader rattles around within the book's narrow universe and repeatedly bumps into the same thing: reiterations of Mr. Johnson's one big idea.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Absolution for Couch Potatoes and Gamers | first = Janet | last = Maslin | date = 26 May 2005 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/26/books/26masl.html | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | accessdate = 22 March 2011}}</ref> In another, [[Walter Kirn]], while acknowledging a lack of science and questioning some of the book's premises with regards to the benefits of reality TV, praised Johnson's \"elegant polemic\", concluding that \"[c]onsidered purely on its own terms, Johnson's thesis holds up despite these quibbles.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = 'Everything Bad Is Good for You': The Couch Potato Path to a Higher I.Q. | first = Walter | last = Kirn | date = 22 May 2005 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/22/books/review/22KIRNL.html |accessdate= 22 March 2011}}</ref> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' gave the book an overall positive review, describing it as \"chock-full of interesting insights that are clearly the reflection of an agile and catholic intellect\", but also suggested that the book is largely built around a [[straw man]] argument and thus \"largely misses the point of the more valid critique of today's pop culture\".<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://www.wired.com/culture/lifestyle/news/2005/05/67611 |title = Everything Bad's Not Bad | first = Suneel |last = Ratan | date = 24 May 2005 | accessdate = 22 March 2011 | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]}}</ref>  ''[[The Guardian]]'' found part of Johnson's thesis \u2014 that some elements of pop culture have grown more complex \u2014 persuasive, but not the second claim that this greater complexity offers any tangible benefits for the public aside from preparing them to handle more complex pop culture; it criticized the shortage of hard science and the conclusions drawn from what science exists and also the application of [[literary theory]] to visual arts media.<ref>{{cite news | title = What Zelda Did | first = Steven | last= Poole |authorlink = Steven Poole| url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/jul/02/highereducation.news | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | date = 2 July 2005 | accessdate = 22 March 2011}}</ref> The [[Associated Press]] review praised the book overall as \"an engaging read\", although it noted that the book was uneven, with TV and video game discussions better than those on film and the internet, and repetitive in presenting its theme.<ref>{{cite news | title = Shelf Life | first = Julie | last = Reed | date = 16 August 2005 | agency = Associated Press | newspaper = [[The Hour (newspaper)|The Hour]] | accessdate = 22 March 2011 | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qRMhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RnUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4334,1941545&dq=everything-bad-is-good-for-you+johnson&hl=en | page = C1, C2}}</ref> [[Salon.com]] described it simply as \"a fine contrarian defense of pop culture\".<ref>{{cite web | title = Hillary, Player Hater | first = Farhad | last = Manjoo | work = [[Salon.com]] | date = 22 July 2005 | accessdate = 22 March 2011 | url = http://dir.salon.com/tech/feature/2005/07/22/grandtheft/ }}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090226225044/http://www.handheldlearning2008.com/handheld-learning-conference-and-exhibition/video/905-video/122-steven-johnson-author Steven Johnson keynote talk] Everything Bad is Good for You, London October 2008\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/24/magazine/24TV.html Watching TV Makes You Smarter], New York Times Magazine\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4663852 Interview], [[National Public Radio]]\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/arts/books/braincandy.html Interview], [[CBC.ca]]\n\n{{Steven Berlin Johnson}}\n\n[[Category:2005 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about the media]]\n[[Category:Popular culture books]]\n[[Category:Books about video games]]\n[[Category:Books about television]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = Everything Bad Is Good for You\n| image         = Everything Bad Cover.JPG\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Everything Bad Is Good for You Cover\n| author        = [[Steven Johnson (author)|Steven Johnson]]\n| cover_artist  = Jamie Keenan\n| country       = \n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| subject       = [[Popular culture]], [[Cultural studies]]\n| publisher     = [[Riverhead Books|Riverhead]]\n| pub_date      = May 2005\n| pages         = 272\n| isbn          = 978-1-59448-194-9\n| congress= HM621 .J64 2006\n| oclc= 69992179\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''Everything Bad Is Good for You: How Today's Popular Culture Is Actually Making Us Smarter''''' is a non-fiction book written by [[Steven Johnson (author)|Steven Johnson]]. Published in 2005, it is based upon Johnson's theory that [[popular culture]] \u2013 in particular [[television program]]s and [[video games]] \u2013 has grown more complex and demanding over time and is making society as a whole more intelligent. The book's claims, especially related to the proposed benefits of television, drew media attention.<ref>{{cite news | title = Fun and Computer Games Make for Smarter Children | date = 4 June 2005 | first = Jim | last = McClellan | newspaper = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]]}}</ref> It received mixed critical reviews.\n\nJohnson states that he aims to persuade readers of \"two things:\n#By almost all the standards we use to measure reading\u2019s cognitive benefits \u2014 attention, memory, following threads, and so on \u2014 the nonliterary popular culture has been steadily growing more challenging over the past thirty years.\n#Increasingly, the nonliterary popular culture is honing ''different'' mental skills that are just as important as the ones exercised by reading books.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title = Everything Bad is Good For You: How Today's Popular Culture is Actually Making Us Smarter|last = Johnson|first = Steven|publisher = Riverhead|year = 2005|isbn = 978-1-59448-194-9|location = |pages = |url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/everythingbadisg00john_0}}</ref>\n\n==Key concepts==\nJohnson challenges the precept that pop culture is deteriorating as a result of new media platforms. He derives the term ''Sleeper Curve'' from the [[Woody Allen]] film ''[[Sleeper (1973 film)|Sleeper]]'', where \"scientists from 2173 are astounded that twentieth-century society failed to grasp the nutritional merits of cream pies and hot fudge\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|last = Johnson|first = Steven|authorlink = |editor = |title = Everything Bad is Good for You|year = 2005|url = https://archive.org/details/everythingbadisg00john_0|format = |accessdate = |edition = |series = |date = |publisher = Riverhead|location = |language = |isbn = 978-1-59448-194-9|oclc = |doi = |id = |pages = |chapter = |chapterurl = |quote = |url-access = registration}}</ref>{{Rp|xvi}} He uses this to argue against contemporary perception of the deteriorating standards of pop culture, although Johnson is quick to point out that by no means does the Sleeper Curve imply that popular culture has become superior to traditional culture.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|132}} Johnson utilizes the following media sources to support his argument:\n\n=== Video games ===\nHe argues that the appeal of video games is not through their (possibly violent or sexual) content, but rather through the fact that the \"structure\" of the [[video games]] uniquely invites exploration and stimulates the [[Reward center of the brain|reward centers of the brain]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|34, 38}} In pointing out arguments for the support of video games, Johnson sheds light on how kids can be more involved in games than in class, but this involvement can teach them that which could be taught in class.<ref name=\":1\" /> To substantiate this argument, he discusses how games and other virtual worlds have immediate rewards, whereas in reality, rewards can take a while to obtain. Johnson states \u201cif you create a  system where rewards are both clearly defined and achieved by exploring an environment, you\u2019ll find human brains drawn to those systems, even if they\u2019re made up of virtual characters and simulated sidewalks. It\u2019s not the subject matter of these games that attracts\u2026it\u2019s the reward system\u201d.<ref name=\":1\" /> Finally, he argues for the support of video games because they also require one to make decisions, whereas books and other forms of art may conjure up imagination and emotions but don\u2019t require decision-making.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nJohnson acknowledges that although the video game industry is growing, the literature on the subject is limited at best. Johnson offers several sources for information on [[Game studies|ludology]]; [http://www.ludology.org/ Ludology.org] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20120919061609/http://seriousgames.org/ seriousgames.org] as well as the books ''Got Game'' by John Beck and Mitchell Wade and ''The Play Ethic'' by [[Pat Kane]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|224\u2013225}}\n\n=== Television and film ===\nJohnson admits that television and film demand less decision-making skills than video games, but also says that the benefits from reading (attention, patience, retention, the parsing of narrative threads, etc.) are making a rise in television and film as well, despite its lack of translating letters to meaning or activating the imagination in quite the same way that books do.<ref name=\":1\" /> He discusses three principles of television and film: \"multiple threading,\" \"flashing arrow,\" and \"social networks.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> \"Multiple threading\", according to Johnson, is marrying complex narrative structure to complex subject matter with multiple plots and subplots (for example, he states that shows like ''ER'' & ''24'' have up to 10 threads per episode).<ref name=\":1\" /> He states that a \"Flashing Arrow\" is a kind of narrative signpost purposely planted to help the audience keep track of what\u2019s going on, but there has been an increasing lack of arrows over the years both, and this lack of arrows is used to draw on intricate plotlines and obscure references.<ref name=\":1\" /> Finally, he states that \"reality shows demand that we track multiple relationships, since the action of these shows revolves around the shifting feuds and alliances between more than a dozen individuals\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> Johnson says this activates social intelligence, defining it as \u201cour ability to monitor and recall many distinct vectors of interaction in the population around us\u201d and, thus, watchers shall be able to better understand social networks.<ref name=\":1\" /> He asserts that television is a \"brilliant medium\" for determining how skilled people are at understanding interpersonal connections, or their [[Autism-spectrum quotient|Autism Quotient]] (the higher a person's emotional intelligence, the lower their \"AQ\"),<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|98\u201399}} and that [[Reality television|reality shows]] in particular realistically display the complexity of \"[[social network]] maps\" in human relations, where a group of people have complex and intertwined engagement.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|108}}\n\nEarlier television, Johnson says, simplified narrative and human relationships, while modern trends not only in reality shows but in \"multiple [[Narrative thread|threading]]\" in scripted programs such as ''[[The Sopranos]]'' improve the audience's cognitive skills.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|67, 72}} He suggests too that modern television and films have reduced the number of \"[[flashing arrow]]s\", narrative clues to help the audience understand the plot, and require audiences to do more cognitive work paying attention to background detail and information if they wish to follow what they are viewing.<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|73\u201374, 77\u201378}}\n\nLater in the book, he mentions that these features of television are also prevalent in film, too.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== The internet ===\nJohnson argues that the internet \u201chas challenged our minds in three fundamental and related ways: by being participatory, by forcing users to learn new interfaces, and by creating new channels for social interaction.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> He uses blogs and utilizing Google to learn things as examples of participation.<ref name=\":1\" /> He declares that \u201caccelerating pace of new platforms and software applications forces users to probe and master new environments\u201d such as \u201clearning the tricks of a new e-mail client, configuring the video chat software properly, getting your bearings after installing a new operating system.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> Additionally, he points out that \u201cin the past few years [the Web has] been [a tool] for augmenting social connection\u201d naming \u201conline personals, social and business network sites such as Friendster, the meetup.com service so central to the political organization of the 2004 campaign.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Overall, he presents evidence to buttress the Internet's benefits.\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe book has received mixed critical reviews. In one ''[[The New York Times]]'' review, [[Janet Maslin]] was primarily negative, dismissing the book's \"facile argument\" and sparsity of hard evidence and claiming that \"The reader rattles around within the book's narrow universe and repeatedly bumps into the same thing: reiterations of Mr. Johnson's one big idea.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Absolution for Couch Potatoes and Gamers | first = Janet | last = Maslin | date = 26 May 2005 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/26/books/26masl.html | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | accessdate = 22 March 2011}}</ref> In another, [[Walter Kirn]], while acknowledging a lack of science and questioning some of the book's premises with regards to the benefits of reality TV, praised Johnson's \"elegant polemic\", concluding that \"[c]onsidered purely on its own terms, Johnson's thesis holds up despite these quibbles.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = 'Everything Bad Is Good for You': The Couch Potato Path to a Higher I.Q. | first = Walter | last = Kirn | date = 22 May 2005 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/22/books/review/22KIRNL.html |accessdate= 22 March 2011}}</ref> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' gave the book an overall positive review, describing it as \"chock-full of interesting insights that are clearly the reflection of an agile and catholic intellect\", but also suggested that the book is largely built around a [[straw man]] argument and thus \"largely misses the point of the more valid critique of today's pop culture\".<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://www.wired.com/culture/lifestyle/news/2005/05/67611 |title = Everything Bad's Not Bad | first = Suneel |last = Ratan | date = 24 May 2005 | accessdate = 22 March 2011 | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]}}</ref>  ''[[The Guardian]]'' found part of Johnson's thesis \u2014 that some elements of pop culture have grown more complex \u2014 persuasive, but not the second claim that this greater complexity offers any tangible benefits for the public aside from preparing them to handle more complex pop culture; it criticized the shortage of hard science and the conclusions drawn from what science exists and also the application of [[literary theory]] to visual arts media.<ref>{{cite news | title = What Zelda Did | first = Steven | last= Poole |authorlink = Steven Poole| url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/jul/02/highereducation.news | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | date = 2 July 2005 | accessdate = 22 March 2011}}</ref> The [[Associated Press]] review praised the book overall as \"an engaging read\", although it noted that the book was uneven, with TV and video game discussions better than those on film and the internet, and repetitive in presenting its theme.<ref>{{cite news | title = Shelf Life | first = Julie | last = Reed | date = 16 August 2005 | agency = Associated Press | newspaper = [[The Hour (newspaper)|The Hour]] | accessdate = 22 March 2011 | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qRMhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RnUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4334,1941545&dq=everything-bad-is-good-for-you+johnson&hl=en | page = C1, C2}}</ref> [[Salon.com]] described it simply as \"a fine contrarian defense of pop culture\".<ref>{{cite web | title = Hillary, Player Hater | first = Farhad | last = Manjoo | work = [[Salon.com]] | date = 22 July 2005 | accessdate = 22 March 2011 | url = http://dir.salon.com/tech/feature/2005/07/22/grandtheft/ }}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090226225044/http://www.handheldlearning2008.com/handheld-learning-conference-and-exhibition/video/905-video/122-steven-johnson-author Steven Johnson keynote talk] Everything Bad is Good for You, London October 2008\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/24/magazine/24TV.html Watching TV Makes You Smarter], New York Times Magazine\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4663852 Interview], [[National Public Radio]]\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/arts/books/braincandy.html Interview], [[CBC.ca]]\n\n{{Steven Berlin Johnson}}\n\n[[Category:2005 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about the media]]\n[[Category:Popular culture books]]\n[[Category:Books about video games]]\n[[Category:Books about television]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: don\u2019t \u2192 don't, what\u2019s \u2192 what's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Everything_Bad_Is_Good_for_You"}
{"title_page": "The Texas Mile", "text_new": "{{Infobox recurring event\n| name         = The Texas Mile<!--Uses page name if omitted-->\n| logo         =\n| logo_caption = \n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| genre        = Auto Show\n| dates        = March and October\n| venue        = [[Victoria Regional Airport]]\n| location     = [[Victoria, TX]]\n| country      = [[United States]]\n| first        = 2003\n| next         = October\n| participants = 250+\n| organized    = \n| website      = {{URL|http://www.texasmile.net/}}\n}}\n'''The Texas Mile''' is a land speed [[auto racing]] event in [[Victoria, Texas]], at the [[Victoria Regional Airport]]. Participants, amateur and professional alike, from across the globe test their fastest standing 1-mile speeds in a wide range of vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gas2.org/2015/04/10/800-hp-zombie-222-electric-mustang-goes-174-mph-at-the-texas-mile/|title=800 HP Zombie 222 Electric Mustang Goes 174 MPH At The Texas Mile|date=2015-04-10|publisher=Gas 2|author=Christopher DeMorro|accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> The bi-annual 3 day motorsports event takes place the last weekend of March and October.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.mysanantonio.com/motorsports/2015/03/texas-mile-returns-to-beeville-on-march-27-29/|title=Texas Mile returns to Beeville on March 27-29 - Motorsports|last=Haag|first=Mike|date=2015-03-22|publisher=San Antonio Express-News - Blog|accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe first Texas Mile event was in October 2003 in [[Goliad, Texas]] with 35 participants and relatively no spectators. The event was co-founded by Jay Matus and his wife, Shannon Matus under J&S Matus Motorsports, Inc. Today, The Texas Mile sells out within hours of opening registration, filling all 220 coveted spots to participate and welcomes thousands of spectators from across the world. The event remained in Goliad, Texas until March 2011 and then relocated to Chase Field Industrial Complex in [[Beeville, Texas]]. In 2017, The Texas Mile relocated to its new \"home\" at the Victoria Regional Airport in Victoria, Texas.\n\nOver 250 sports cars, motorcycles, trucks and concept race cars participate in the standing 1-Mile event on an airport runway strip with 1/2 Mile to shutdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/4/1/8320189/zombie-222-electric-car-1968-mustang-texas-mile|title=Dark Horse: the story of a record-shattering, all-electric \u201968 Mustang|last=Zelenko|first=Michael|date=2015-04-01|publisher=The Verge|accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> Participants come from all over the United States, Finland, Saudi Arabia, Mexico, Canada, etc.\n\nThe current Texas Mile record is held by M2K Motorsports' 2006 [[Ford GT]], driven by Patrick O'Gorman, clocking in at 300.4 MPH.  The record-setting speed was achieved during the March 2019 Texas Mile event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/news/27135/ford-gt-with-2500-hp-hits-300-4-mph-at-the-texas-mile-sets-new-standing-mile-record|title=Ford GT With 2,500 HP Hits 300.4 MPH at the Texas Mile, Sets New Standing Mile Record|last=Perez|first=Jerry|date=2019-03-25|publisher=The Drive|accessdate=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\nAn important milestone for electric vehicles was reached at the Texas Mile when Mitch Medford drove his 800-horsepower 1968 [[Ford Mustang|Mustang]] fastback, the Zombie 222, to an electric vehicle speed record of 178 mph in March 2015.  As of October 2016, the Zombie 222 also holds the record as the world's fastest-accelerating (modified) road car with a 0-60 mph time of 1.79 seconds.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.texasmile.net/ Official site]\n\n[[Category:Auto races in the United States]]\n[[Category:Auto shows in the United States]]\n[[Category:Victoria, Texas]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox recurring event\n| name         = The Texas Mile<!--Uses page name if omitted-->\n| logo         =\n| logo_caption = \n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| genre        = Auto Show\n| dates        = March and October\n| venue        = [[Victoria Regional Airport]]\n| location     = [[Victoria, TX]]\n| country      = [[United States]]\n| first        = 2003\n| next         = October\n| participants = 250+\n| organized    = \n| website      = {{URL|http://www.texasmile.net/}}\n}}\n'''The Texas Mile''' is a land speed [[auto racing]] event in [[Victoria, Texas]], at the [[Victoria Regional Airport]]. Participants, amateur and professional alike, from across the globe test their fastest standing 1-mile speeds in a wide range of vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gas2.org/2015/04/10/800-hp-zombie-222-electric-mustang-goes-174-mph-at-the-texas-mile/|title=800 HP Zombie 222 Electric Mustang Goes 174 MPH At The Texas Mile|date=2015-04-10|publisher=Gas 2|author=Christopher DeMorro|accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> The bi-annual 3 day motorsports event takes place the last weekend of March and October.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.mysanantonio.com/motorsports/2015/03/texas-mile-returns-to-beeville-on-march-27-29/|title=Texas Mile returns to Beeville on March 27-29 - Motorsports|last=Haag|first=Mike|date=2015-03-22|publisher=San Antonio Express-News - Blog|accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe first Texas Mile event was in October 2003 in [[Goliad, Texas]] with 35 participants and relatively no spectators. The event was co-founded by Jay Matus and his wife, Shannon Matus under J&S Matus Motorsports, Inc. Today, The Texas Mile sells out within hours of opening registration, filling all 220 coveted spots to participate and welcomes thousands of spectators from across the world. The event remained in Goliad, Texas until March 2011 and then relocated to Chase Field Industrial Complex in [[Beeville, Texas]]. In 2017, The Texas Mile relocated to its new \"home\" at the Victoria Regional Airport in Victoria, Texas.\n\nOver 250 sports cars, motorcycles, trucks and concept race cars participate in the standing 1-Mile event on an airport runway strip with 1/2 Mile to shutdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/4/1/8320189/zombie-222-electric-car-1968-mustang-texas-mile|title=Dark Horse: the story of a record-shattering, all-electric \u201968 Mustang|last=Zelenko|first=Michael|date=2015-04-01|publisher=The Verge|accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> Participants come from all over the United States, Finland, Saudi Arabia, Mexico, Canada, etc.\n\nThe current Texas Mile record is held by M2K Motorsports' 2006 [[Ford GT]], driven by Patrick O'Gorman, clocking in at 300.4 MPH.  The record-setting speed was achieved during the March 2019 Texas Mile event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/news/27135/ford-gt-with-2500-hp-hits-300-4-mph-at-the-texas-mile-sets-new-standing-mile-record|title=Ford GT With 2,500 HP Hits 300.4 MPH at the Texas Mile, Sets New Standing Mile Record|last=Perez|first=Jerry|date=2019-03-25|publisher=The Drive|accessdate=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\nAn important milestone for electric vehicles was reached at the Texas Mile when Mitch Medford drove his 800 horsepower 1968 [[Ford Mustang|Mustang]] fastback, the Zombie 222, to an electric vehicle speed record of 178 mph in March of 2015.  As of October 2016, the Zombie 222 also holds the record as the world's fastest-accelerating (modified) road car with a 0-60 mph time of 1.79 seconds.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.texasmile.net/ Official site]\n\n[[Category:Auto races in the United States]]\n[[Category:Auto shows in the United States]]\n[[Category:Victoria, Texas]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Texas]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: March of 2015 \u2192 March 2015, 800 horsepower \u2192 800-horsepower", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Texas_Mile"}
{"title_page": "Zhao Lijian", "text_new": "{{Expand Chinese|\u8d75\u7acb\u575a|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Chinese politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image    = \n|caption = \n|office1       = Deputy Director of Foreign Ministry Information Department of the People's Republic of China\n|term_start1   = August 2019\n|term_end1     = \n|predecessor1  = \n|successor1    = \n|1blankname1   = Director\n|1namedata1    = [[Hua Chunying]]\n|office2       = \n|term_start2   = \n|term_end2     = \n|predecessor2  = \n|successor2    = \n|office3       = \n|term_start3   = \n|term_end3     = \n|predecessor3  = \n|successor3    = \n|name       = Zhao Lijian\n|native_name= \u8d75\u7acb\u575a\n|native_name_lang= zh\n|birthname  = \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|11|10}}  \n|birth_place= [[Hebei]], China\n|death_date = <!--  {{death date and age|}} or {{death year and age| }} -->\n|death_place= \n|party      = [[Communist Party of China]]\n|spouse     = <!--  {{marriage||}}  -->\n|children   = \n|parents    = \n|relations  = \n|religion   = \n|profession = \n|alma_mater = [[Korea Development Institute]]\n|website    = \n|signature  = \n|footnotes  =\n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u8d75|\u7acb|\u575a}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u8d99|\u7acb|\u5805}}\n|p = Zh\u00e0o L\u00ecji\u0101n \n|w = \n}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Zhao (surname)|Zhao]]}}\n\n'''Zhao Lijian''' ({{zh|s=\u8d75\u7acb\u575a|p=Zh\u00e0o L\u00ecji\u0101n}}; born 10 November 1972) is a Chinese politician and the current deputy director of Foreign Ministry Information Department. He is the 31st spokesperson since the position was established in the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|ministry]] back in 1983.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Huang Yuqin ({{lang|zh|\u9ec4\u94b0\u94a6}})|url=http://www.chinanews.com/gn/2020/02-24/9102792.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u65b0\u4efb\u53d1\u8a00\u4eba\u8d75\u7acb\u575a\u4eae\u76f8 \u7cfb\u8d44\u6df1\u5916\u4ea4\u5b98\u5c65\u5386\u4e30\u5bcc |work=chinanews.com |date=24 February 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020 |language=zh}}</ref> He joined the Foreign Service in 1996 and has served primarily in Asia. Zhao gained notoriety during his time serving in [[Pakistan]] for his outspoken use of [[Twitter]],<ref>{{cite news |author1=Owen Churchill |title=Chinese diplomat Zhao Lijian, known for his Twitter outbursts, is given senior foreign ministry post |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3024180/chinese-diplomat-zhao-lijian-known-his-twitter-outbursts-given |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=24 August 2019}}</ref><ref name = \"CNNMarch14\">{{cite news |last1=Wescott |first1=Ben |last2=Jiang |first2=Steven |title=Chinese diplomat promotes conspiracy theory that US military brought coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=14 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200313204557/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html |archivedate=14 March 2020}}</ref> a social network [[Websites blocked in mainland China|website that is blocked]] within China.\n\n==Biography==\nZhao was born in [[Hebei]] on November 10, 1972. He joined the [[Department of Asian Affairs (People's Republic of China)|Department of Asian Affairs]] in 1996. He obtained a master's degree in public policy from the [[Korea Development Institute]] in 2005. In 2009, he became secretary of the [[Embassy of China in Washington, D.C.]] In 2013, he was recalled to the Department of Asian Affairs. From 2015 to August 2019, he served as counsellor and minister counsellor of the Chinese Embassy in Pakistan. \n\nZhao became well known for his frequent use of [[Twitter]] to criticize the United States, including on topics such as race relations and the [[United States foreign policy in the Middle East]].<ref name=\"zhao-us\">{{cite news |title=Meet The Chinese Diplomat Who Got Promoted For Trolling The US On Twitter |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/bensmith/zhao-lijian-china-twitter |work=BuzzFeed News |date=2 December 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, he engaged in a contentious dispute with [[Susan Rice]], a former national security advisor to President [[Barack Obama]], regarding China's [[Xinjiang re-education camps|mass internment of Uighurs]] in [[Xinjiang]]. Susan Rice called him a \"racist disgrace\",<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhou |first1=Laura |title=Former US national security adviser Susan Rice calls Chinese diplomat Zhao Lijian \u2018a racist disgrace\u2019 after Twitter tirade |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3018676/susan-rice-calls-chinese-diplomat-zhao-lijian-racist-disgrace |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=15 July 2019 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200322114644/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3018676/susan-rice-calls-chinese-diplomat-zhao-lijian-racist-disgrace |archivedate=22 March 2020}}</ref> and the dispute raised Zhao's profile in Beijing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhai |first1=Keith |last2=Tian |first2=Yew Lun |title=In China, a young diplomat rises as aggressive foreign policy takes root |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-diplomacy-insight/in-china-a-young-diplomat-rises-as-aggressive-foreign-policy-takes-root-idUSKBN21I0F8 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"zhao-us\"/>\n\nHe has been deputy director of Foreign Ministry Information Department of the People's Republic of China since August 2019.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Yue Huairang ({{lang|zh|\u5cb3\u6000\u8ba9}})|url=https://www.thepaper.cn/newsDetail_forward_4236108 |script-title=zh:\u8d75\u7acb\u575a\u51fa\u4efb\u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u65b0\u95fb\u53f8\u526f\u53f8\u957f|trans-title=Zhao Lijian appointed deputy director of Foreign Ministry Information Department |work=thepaper.cn |date=23 August 2019 |accessdate=5 March 2020 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Zhao began to openly endorse a [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#US biological_weapon|conspiracy theory regarding the origin of COVID-19]], arguing that rather than originating naturally in [[Wuhan]], the disease was actually a biological weapon developed by the United States military.<ref>{{cite news |title=US military may have brought virus to Wuhan, tweets China |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2020/03/13/us-military-may-have-brought-virus-to-wuhan-tweets-china |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] |date=13 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200324074905/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2020/03/13/us-military-may-have-brought-virus-to-wuhan-tweets-china |archivedate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name = \"CNNMarch14\"/> Zhao tweeted that the disease may have been introduced by members of the [[United States Army]] who visited Wuhan during the [[2019 Military World Games]] in October 2019.<ref name = \"CNNMarch14\"/> Zhao later posted an article he said provided \"further evidence that the virus originated in the US\".<ref name=\"ABC\">Walden, Max. [https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-13/coronavirus-originated-in-united-states-china-official-says/12055278 \"Coronavirus began in US, not China, Chinese official suggests\"] [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]. March 13, 2020.</ref> The article cited a Chinese study, covered by ''[[Global Times]]'', a tabloid run by the ruling [[Communist Party|Communist Party]]'s official ''[[People's Daily]]''.<ref name=\"buzzfeed-zhao\">{{cite news |title=Chinese Diplomats Are Pushing Conspiracy Theories That The Coronavirus Didn't Originate In China |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/chinese-diplomats-are-pushing-conspiracy-theories-that-the |work=BuzzFeed News |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The article was published by the [[Centre for Research on Globalization]], which has been accused of promoting conspiracy theories and anti-Western propaganda.<ref name=\"ABC\"/> The [[United States Department of State]] subsequently summoned Chinese Ambassador [[Cui Tiankai]] over Zhao's remarks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delaney |first1=Robert |title=US summons Ambassador Cui Tiankai amid anger over Beijing\u2019s virus comments |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/3075193/us-summoning-chinese-ambassador-over-beijing-coronavirus-comments |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |agency=South China Morning Post |date=14 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Cui publicly disavowed Zhao's statements in a later interview with [[Axios (website)|Axios]], indicating a potential rift within the Chinese government over how to handle Zhao's rhetoric. Zhao was absent from Foreign Ministry press conferences for several weeks following Cui's remarks, and declined to portray his comments as official positions of the Chinese government.<ref name=\"BloombergApril2020\">{{cite news |title=China Spokesman Defends Virus Tweets Criticized by Trump |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-07/china-spokesman-defends-virus-tweets-criticized-by-trump |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Bloomberg |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nZhao condemned U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] for using the term \"Wuhan virus.\"<ref name=\"buzzfeed-zhao\"/> He also criticized [[Fox News]] for calling COVID-19 the \"Chinese coronavirus\" and accused [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] of racism and xenophobia.<ref name=\"buzzfeed-zhao\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://twitter.com/zlj517/ Zhao Lijian's Twitter]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhao, Lijian}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China politicians from Hebei]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of China politicians from Hebei]]\n[[Category:Spokespersons for the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Chinese expatriates in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Chinese|\u8d75\u7acb\u575a|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Chinese politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image    = \n|caption = \n|office1       = Deputy Director of Foreign Ministry Information Department of the People's Republic of China\n|term_start1   = August 2019\n|term_end1     = \n|predecessor1  = \n|successor1    = \n|1blankname1   = Director\n|1namedata1    = [[Hua Chunying]]\n|office2       = \n|term_start2   = \n|term_end2     = \n|predecessor2  = \n|successor2    = \n|office3       = \n|term_start3   = \n|term_end3     = \n|predecessor3  = \n|successor3    = \n|name       = Zhao Lijian\n|native_name= \u8d75\u7acb\u575a\n|native_name_lang= zh\n|birthname  = \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|11|10}}  \n|birth_place= [[Hebei]], China\n|death_date = <!--  {{death date and age|}} or {{death year and age| }} -->\n|death_place= \n|party      = [[Communist Party of China]]\n|spouse     = <!--  {{marriage||}}  -->\n|children   = \n|parents    = \n|relations  = \n|religion   = \n|profession = \n|alma_mater = [[Korea Development Institute]]\n|website    = \n|signature  = \n|footnotes  =\n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u8d75|\u7acb|\u575a}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u8d99|\u7acb|\u5805}}\n|p = Zh\u00e0o L\u00ecji\u0101n \n|w = \n}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Zhao (surname)|Zhao]]}}\n\n'''Zhao Lijian''' ({{zh|s=\u8d75\u7acb\u575a|p=Zh\u00e0o L\u00ecji\u0101n}}; born 10 November 1972) is a Chinese politician and the current deputy director of Foreign Ministry Information Department. He is the 31st spokesperson since the position was established in the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|ministry]] back in 1983.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Huang Yuqin ({{lang|zh|\u9ec4\u94b0\u94a6}})|url=http://www.chinanews.com/gn/2020/02-24/9102792.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u65b0\u