h as race relations and the [[United States foreign policy in the Middle East]].<ref name=\"zhao-us\">{{cite news |title=Meet The Chinese Diplomat Who Got Promoted For Trolling The US On Twitter |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/bensmith/zhao-lijian-china-twitter |work=BuzzFeed News |date=2 December 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, he engaged in a contentious dispute with [[Susan Rice]], a former national security advisor to President [[Barack Obama]], regarding China's [[Xinjiang re-education camps|mass internment of Uighurs]] in [[Xinjiang]]. Susan Rice called him a \"racist disgrace\",<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhou |first1=Laura |title=Former US national security adviser Susan Rice calls Chinese diplomat Zhao Lijian \u2018a racist disgrace\u2019 after Twitter tirade |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3018676/susan-rice-calls-chinese-diplomat-zhao-lijian-racist-disgrace |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=15 July 2019 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200322114644/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3018676/susan-rice-calls-chinese-diplomat-zhao-lijian-racist-disgrace |archivedate=22 March 2020}}</ref> and the dispute raised Zhao's profile in Beijing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhai |first1=Keith |last2=Tian |first2=Yew Lun |title=In China, a young diplomat rises as aggressive foreign policy takes root |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-diplomacy-insight/in-china-a-young-diplomat-rises-as-aggressive-foreign-policy-takes-root-idUSKBN21I0F8 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"zhao-us\"/>\n\nHe has been deputy director of Foreign Ministry Information Department of the People's Republic of China since August 2019.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Yue Huairang ({{lang|zh|\u5cb3\u6000\u8ba9}})|url=https://www.thepaper.cn/newsDetail_forward_4236108 |script-title=zh:\u8d75\u7acb\u575a\u51fa\u4efb\u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u65b0\u95fb\u53f8\u526f\u53f8\u957f|trans-title=Zhao Lijian appointed deputy director of Foreign Ministry Information Department |work=thepaper.cn |date=23 August 2019 |accessdate=5 March 2020 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Zhao began to openly endorse a [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#US biological_weapon|conspiracy theory regarding the origin of COVID-19]], arguing that rather than originating naturally in [[Wuhan]], the disease was actually a biological weapon developed by the United States military.<ref>{{cite news |title=US military may have brought virus to Wuhan, tweets China |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2020/03/13/us-military-may-have-brought-virus-to-wuhan-tweets-china |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] |date=13 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200324074905/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2020/03/13/us-military-may-have-brought-virus-to-wuhan-tweets-china |archivedate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name = \"CNNMarch14\"/> Zhao tweeted that the disease may have been introduced by members of the [[United States Army]] who visited Wuhan during the [[2019 Military World Games]] in October 2019.<ref name = \"CNNMarch14\"/> Zhao later posted an article he said provided \"further evidence that the virus originated in the US\".<ref name=\"ABC\">Walden, Max. [https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-13/coronavirus-originated-in-united-states-china-official-says/12055278 \"Coronavirus began in US, not China, Chinese official suggests\"] [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]. March 13, 2020.</ref> The article cited a Chinese study, covered by ''[[Global Times]]'', a tabloid run by the ruling [[Communist Party|Communist Party]]'s official ''[[People's Daily]]''.<ref name=\"buzzfeed-zhao\">{{cite news |title=Chinese Diplomats Are Pushing Conspiracy Theories That The Coronavirus Didn't Originate In China |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/chinese-diplomats-are-pushing-conspiracy-theories-that-the |work=BuzzFeed News |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The article was published by the [[Centre for Research on Globalization]], which has been accused of promoting conspiracy theories and anti-Western propaganda.<ref name=\"ABC\"/> The [[United States Department of State]] subsequently summoned Chinese Ambassador [[Cui Tiankai]] over Zhao's remarks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delaney |first1=Robert |title=US summons Ambassador Cui Tiankai amid anger over Beijing\u2019s virus comments |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/3075193/us-summoning-chinese-ambassador-over-beijing-coronavirus-comments |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |agency=South China Morning Post |date=14 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Cui publicly disavowed Zhao's statements in a later interview with [[Axios]], indicating a potential rift within the Chinese government over how to handle Zhao's rhetoric. Zhao was absent from Foreign Ministry press conferences for several weeks following Cui's remarks, and declined to portray his comments as official positions of the Chinese government.<ref name=\"BloombergApril2020\">{{cite news |title=China Spokesman Defends Virus Tweets Criticized by Trump |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-07/china-spokesman-defends-virus-tweets-criticized-by-trump |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Bloomberg |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nZhao condemned U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] for using the term \"Wuhan virus.\"<ref name=\"buzzfeed-zhao\"/> He also criticized [[Fox News]] for calling COVID-19 the \"Chinese coronavirus\" and accused [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] of racism and xenophobia.<ref name=\"buzzfeed-zhao\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://twitter.com/zlj517/ Zhao Lijian's Twitter]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhao, Lijian}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China politicians from Hebei]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of China politicians from Hebei]]\n[[Category:Spokespersons for the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Chinese expatriates in Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "WhinyTheYounger", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhao_Lijian"}
{"title_page": "Vernon E. Megee", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Vernon Edgar Megee\n|image= Vernon Megee.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= Lieutenant General Vernon E. Megee\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1900|06|05}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1992|01|14|1900|06|05}}\n|birth_place= [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n|death_place= [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]\n|placeofburial= [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n|nickname= \n|allegiance= {{flag|United States}}\n|branch= [[File:USMC logo.svg|25px]]&nbsp;[[United States Marine Corps]]\n|serviceyears= 1919\u20131959\n|rank= [[File:US-O10 insignia.svg|42px]] [[General (United States)|General]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[Marine Corps Air Station, Cherry Point|MCAS Cherry Point]]<br/>[[1st Marine Aircraft Wing]]<br/>[[Fleet Marine Force, Atlantic]]<br/>[[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps]]<br/>[[Fleet Marine Force, Pacific]]\n|battles= [[World War II]]\n* [[Battle of Iwo Jima]]\n* [[Battle of Okinawa]]\n|awards= [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] with [[Combat \"V\"]]<br/>[[Navy and Marine Corps Medal]]<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] with Combat \"V\"\n|relations= \n|laterwork= Superintendent, Marine Military Academy\n}}\n[[General (United States)|General]] '''Vernon Edgar Megee''' (June 5, 1900 \u2013 January 14, 1992) was a [[United States Marine Corps]] [[General (United States)|general]]. He is recognized as a pioneer in the development of [[close air support]] for ground combat operations.<ref name=MCLM>\"[[#MCLM|General Vernon E. Megee, USMC]]\", Marine Corps Legacy Museum.</ref> He served as [[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps]] from 1956 to 1957; with his final billet from 1957 to 1959 as commanding general, Fleet Marine Force, Pacific. When he retired from the Marine Corps, after 40 years of active duty service, he received a [[List of United States Marine Corps four-star generals#Tombstone generals|promotion]] to [[4-star rank]].\n\n==Biography==\nVernon Megee was born in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], on June 5, 1900. After attending [[Oklahoma A&M College]] from 1917 to 1919, he enlisted in the Marine Corps in 1919, and spent the next two years on [[garrison]] duty at [[Marine Corps Recruit Depot Parris Island|Parris Island]], South Carolina.<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology>\"Chronology\", ''[[#PapersEisenhower|Vernon E. Megee Papers]]'', Eisenhower Library.</ref> In 1921, he was selected for [[Officer Candidates School (U.S. Marine Corps)|Officer Candidate School]] (OCS).\n\n===Early Marine Corps career \u2014 1920s===\nIn 1922, upon graduation from OCS, Megee was commissioned a [[Second Lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]]. For the next several years he held many positions in Marine forces stationed abroad, including one tour of duty in Haiti and two tours of duty in China. He served his first tour of expeditionary duty with the 1st Marine Brigade in Haiti from October 1923 to November 1925.<ref name=WhosWho_Megee/> He was then stationed with the 10th Marines at Quantico, Virginia. He was promoted to first lieutenant in March 1926. In April 1927 Megee deployed to China on his second tour of expeditionary duty. On return to the States in March 1928, he was assigned to preliminary aviation training at the Naval Air Station, San Diego, California. In January 1929 he began another tour of expeditionary service as Squadrons Quartermaster, Aircraft Squadrons, 2nd Marine Brigade, in Nicaragua.<ref name=MCG_Ulbrich_200611>{{cite journal|accessdate=March 6, 2009\n|url=http://www.marinecorpsgazette-digital.com/marinecorpsgazette-share/200611/?pg=76\n|journal=[[Marine Corps Gazette]] |date=November 2006\n|title=Revisiting Small Wars: A 1933 questionnaire, Vernon E. Megee, and the ''Small Wars Manual'' \n|first=David J. |last=Ulbrich}}</ref> After earning the [[Navy and Marine Corps Medal]] there, he returned to the United States to enter flight training at Pensacola, Florida in January 1931.\n\n===Marine aviator \u2014 1930s===\nIn February 1932 he qualified as a [[naval aviator]],<ref name=WhosWho_Megee/> and was assigned to Aircraft Squadrons, West Coast Expeditionary Forces in San Diego, California. From June 1933 to August 1936, he was an instructor at the Marine Corps School in [[Marine Corps Base Quantico|Quantico]], Virginia.<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/> From the period of August 1936 to June 1939, he attended the Air Corps Tactical School at Maxwell Field in Alabama, after which he returned to Quantico as an instructor until July 1939.<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/> From July 1939 until 1940, he was Commander of Marine Fighter Squadron 2, [[2nd Marine Aircraft Wing]].  From 1940 to 1943, Megee was the [[Executive officer#United States|executive officer]] of the U.S. Naval Aviation Mission to [[Peru]].<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/>\n\n===World War II; 1940s===\nIn November 1943, Megee checked into [[Marine Corps Air Station Cherry Point]] and was designated as the Chief of Staff of the [[3rd Marine Aircraft Wing]] (3d MAW). At the time 3d MAW was in charge of pilot training.<ref name=Megee_p103>{{harvnb|Megee|2011|p=103}}</ref>  In the spring of 1944, 3d MAW was designated to go to Hawaii to absorb the functions of Marine Air, Hawaiian Area. Megee left the United States in late April on board the {{USS|Hoggatt Bay|CVE-75}}.<ref name=Megee_p107>{{harvnb|Megee|2011|p=107}}</ref> He remained with the 3d Marine Aircraft Wing as they got established at [[Marine Corps Air Station Ewa]] in May 1944. In October 1944, Colonel Magee was named as the commanding officer of Provisional Air Support Command whose role was to organize, train and equip Marine units to duplicate the air control function of the navy but do it ashore.<ref name=Megee_p110>{{harvnb|Megee|2011|p=110}}</ref> He served in combat in World War II on Iwo Jima and Okinawa. During the [[Battle of Iwo Jima]], he was commander of Landing Force Air Support Control Unit One. For his service in this capacity, he was awarded the [[Legion of Merit]] with Combat \"V\".<ref name=WhosWho_Megee>\"[[#WhosWho|General Vernon E. Megee, USMC]]\", ''Who's Who in Marine Corps History''.</ref>  During  the [[Battle of Okinawa]], he commanded all the Marine Landing Force Air Support Control units, for which he was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]] with Combat \"V\".<ref name=WhosWho_Megee/>\n\n===1950s \u2014 Commands, Assistant Commandant===\n[[File:Marine Corps Birthday Celebration, Korea, 1953 (15533124739).jpg|right|thumb|Megee during the 1953 [[United States Marine Corps birthday|Marine Corps Birthday]] in Korea.]]\nAfter the war, he became an instructor at the [[National War College]], and was promoted to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] in December 1946. From January 1947 to January 1950, he served as assistant director of Marine Corps Aviation.<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/>\n\nMegee finished his [[bachelor's degree]] with Oklahoma A&M in 1950, and then served in a variety of positions in the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] and held several commands: [[Marine Corps Air Station, Cherry Point]] Commanding General, Aircraft, [[Fleet Marine Force, Pacific]], [[First Marine Aircraft Wing]], and commanding general, Aircraft, [[Fleet Marine Force, Atlantic]]. He commanded the 1st Marine Aircraft Wing during the [[Korean War]] from January to December, 1953. He was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] for his service during this time.<ref name=MCLM/><ref>http://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=42339</ref>\n\nHe was promoted to lieutenant general in January 1956. From January 1956 to December 1957, he was [[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps|Assistant Commandant]] and Chief of Staff of the Marine Corps.,<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/> the first Marine aviator to serve as assistant commandant.<ref name=NYT_Lambert_19920119>[[#LambertNYT|Lambert]], ''New York Times'', 1992.</ref> Then from December 1957 to November 1959, he was the commanding general of the Fleet Marine Force, Pacific.<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/>\n\nMegee retired from the Marine Corps in November 1959 and was advanced to the rank of general upon retirement by reason of having been specially commended in combat.<ref name=WhosWho_Megee/>\n\n===In retirement===\nAfter retirement, he settled in [[Austin, Texas]], and attended graduate school at the [[University of Texas]], earning his [[Master of Arts]] degree in 1963 \u2013 writing a Master's thesis titled \"United States Military Intervention in Nicaragua, 1902\u20131932.\"<ref name=MCG_Ulbrich_200611/> He helped organize the [[Marine Military Academy]] at [[Harlingen, Texas]], where he served as superintendent and president of the board of trustees from 1964 to 1988. He was a member of the [[National Rifle Association]] and wrote numerous articles on firearms for various sporting magazines.\n\nMegee died in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], on January 14, 1992, at age 91 and was buried with [[military funeral|full military honors]] at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref name=ANC>\"[[#ANC|Vernon E. Megee, General, USMC]]\", ArlingtonCemetery.net.</ref>\n\n==Awards and decorations==\nMegee's awards and decorations include: <center>\n{|\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[File:Naval Aviator Badge.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg |width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|other_device=nv|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|other_device=nv|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Marine Corps Good Conduct ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Marine Corps Expeditionary ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Nicaraguan Campaign ribbon 1933.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Yangtze Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=American Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=American Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=Asiatic-Pacific Campaign ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=World War II Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=Korean_Service_Medal_-_Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Peruvian Cross of Aeronautical Merit.jpg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Taeguk Cordon Medal.png|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Presidential Unit Citation (Korea).svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Phliber rib.png|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=United Nations Service Medal Korea ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|} \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"14\" align=\"center\" |[[United States Aviator Badge|Naval Aviator Badge]]\n|-\n!1st<br />Row\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Legion of Merit]] w/ [[Combat \"V\"]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Navy and Marine Corps Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Bronze Star Medal]] w/ Combat \"V\"\n|-\n!2nd<br />Row\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Navy Unit Commendation]] w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" [[Service star|bronze star]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Good Conduct Medal (United States)|Marine Corps Good Conduct Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Marine Corps Expeditionary Medal]] w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze star\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Nicaraguan Campaign Medal|Nicaraguan Campaign Medal (1933)]]\n|-\n!3rd<br />Row\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Yangtze Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[American Defense Service Medal]] w/ Base [[medal bar|clasp]] ({{frac|3|16}}\" [[Service star|bronze star]])\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[American Campaign Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Asiatic-Pacific Campaign Medal]] w/ three {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze stars\n|-\n!4th<br />Row\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[World War II Victory Medal (United States)|World War II Victory Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[National Defense Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Korean Service Medal]] w/ two {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze stars\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |Peruvian Aviation Cross\n|-\n!5th<br />Row\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Order of Military Merit (Korea)|Order of Military Merit, Taeguk Cordon Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Presidential Unit Citation (Korea)|Republic of Korea Presidential Unit Citation]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[Philippine Liberation Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[United Nations Korea Medal]]\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box|\n title=Commanding General of the [[Fleet Marine Force, Pacific]]|\n before= [[Edwin A. Pollock]]|\n years= December 1, 1957 - November 1, 1959|\n after= [[Thomas A. Wornham]]\n}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps]]|\n before= [[Randolph M. Pate]]|\n years= January 1, 1956 - November 30, 1957|\n after= [[Verne J. McCaul]]\n}}\n{{Succession box|\n title=Commanding General of the [[1st Marine Aircraft Wing]]|\n before= [[Clayton C. Jerome]] |\n years= January 9, 1953 - December 7, 1953|\n after= [[Albert D. Cooley]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|World War II}}\n\n*[[Close air support]]\n*[[List of United States Marine Corps four-star generals]]\n*[[Commandant of the Marine Corps]]\n*[[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n;Bibliography\n*{{citation|last = Megee|first = Vernon E.|year = 2011|title = Memoirs of a Marine: Old Corps \u2013 New Corps 1919 to 1959|publisher = Atriad Press|location = [[Dallas, Texas]]|isbn = 978-1-933177-28-1}}\n\n;Web\n*{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.tecom.usmc.mil/HD/Whos_Who/Megee_VE.htm\n |title        = General Vernon E. Megee, USMC\n |work         = Who's Who in Marine Corps History\n |publisher    = History Division, United States Marine Corps\n |ref          = WhosWho\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110615091538/http://www.tecom.usmc.mil/HD/Whos_Who/Megee_VE.htm\n |archive-date = 2011-06-15\n |url-status     = dead\n}}\n*{{cite news|accessdate=\n|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE6DB123FF93AA25752C0A964958260 \n|title=Gen. Vernon E. Megee, 91, Dies; Was Pioneer in Combat Aviation\n|first=Bruce |last=Lambert |date=January 19, 1992\n|work=[[New York Times]]\n|ref=LambertNYT}}\n*{{cite web|accessdate=March 6, 2009\n|url=http://eisenhower.archives.gov/Research/Finding_Aids/PDFs/Megee_Vernon_Papers.pdf\n|title=Papers of Vernon E. Megee |format=PDF\n|publisher=[[Eisenhower Presidential Center|Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library]]\n|ref=PapersEisenhower}}\n*{{cite web|accessdate=\n|date=28 January 2006\n|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/vemegee.htm \n|title=Vernon E. Megee, General, United States Marine Corps\n|publisher=Arlingtoncemetery.net\n|ref=ANC}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal\n|last=Megee |first=MajGen Vernon E., USMC\n|title=Tactical Air Support of Ground Forces\n|journal=[[Marine Corps Gazette]] |volume= 39 |issue=13\n|date=December 1955}}\n\n*{{cite web|accessdate=March 6, 2009\n|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/1992/MSH.htm\n|title=The Improved Direct Air Support Center\n|first= Major Steven H., USMC |last=Mattos\n|publisher=GlobalSecurity.org}}\n\n*{{cite journal \n|title=Airpower and Restraint in Small Wars: Marine Corps Aviation in the Second Nicaraguan Campaign, 1927\u201333 |first=Wray R. |last=Johnson\n|journal=Aerospace Power Journal |date= Fall  2001 |publisher=[[United States Air Force]]}}\n\n{{CMC}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Megee, Vernon}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People of the Banana Wars]]\n[[Category:People from Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps generals]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy and Marine Corps Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Military Merit (Korea)]]\n[[Category:Battle of Iwo Jima]]\n[[Category:Air Corps Tactical School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Vernon Edgar Megee\n|image= Vernon Megee.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= Lieutenant General Vernon E. Megee\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1900|06|05}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1992|01|14|1900|06|05}}\n|birth_place= [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n|death_place= [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]\n|placeofburial= [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n|nickname= \n|allegiance= {{flag|United States}}\n|branch= [[File:USMC logo.svg|25px]]&nbsp;[[United States Marine Corps]]\n|serviceyears= 1919\u20131959\n|rank= [[File:US-O10 insignia.svg|42px]] [[General (United States)|General]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[Marine Corps Air Station, Cherry Point|MCAS Cherry Point]]<br/>[[1st Marine Aircraft Wing]]<br/>[[Fleet Marine Force, Atlantic]]<br/>[[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps]]<br/>[[Fleet Marine Force, Pacific]]\n|battles= [[World War II]]\n* [[Battle of Iwo Jima]]\n* [[Battle of Okinawa]]\n|awards= [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] with [[Combat \"V\"]]<br/>[[Navy and Marine Corps Medal]]<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] with Combat \"V\"\n|relations= \n|laterwork= Superintendent, Marine Military Academy\n}}\n[[General (United States)|General]] '''Vernon Edgar Megee''' (June 5, 1900 \u2013 January 14, 1992) was a [[United States Marine Corps]] [[General (United States)|general]]. He is recognized as a pioneer in the development of [[close air support]] for ground combat operations.<ref name=MCLM>\"[[#MCLM|General Vernon E. Megee, USMC]]\", Marine Corps Legacy Museum.</ref> He served as [[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps]] from 1956 to 1957; with his final billet from 1957 to 1959 as commanding general, Fleet Marine Force, Pacific. When he retired from the Marine Corps, after 40 years of active duty service, he received a [[List of United States Marine Corps four-star generals#Tombstone generals|promotion]] to [[4-star rank]].\n\n==Biography==\nVernon Megee was born in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], on June 5, 1900. After attending [[Oklahoma A&M College]] from 1917 to 1919, he enlisted in the Marine Corps in 1919, and spent the next two years on [[garrison]] duty at [[Marine Corps Recruit Depot Parris Island|Parris Island]], South Carolina.<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology>\"Chronology\", ''[[#PapersEisenhower|Vernon E. Megee Papers]]'', Eisenhower Library.</ref> In 1921, he was selected for [[Officer Candidates School (U.S. Marine Corps)|Officer Candidate School]] (OCS).\n\n===Early Marine Corps career \u2014 1920s===\nIn 1922, upon graduation from OCS, Megee was commissioned a [[Second Lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]]. For the next several years he held many positions in Marine forces stationed abroad, including one tour of duty in Haiti and two tours of duty in China. He served his first tour of expeditionary duty with the 1st Marine Brigade in Haiti from October 1923 to November 1925.<ref name=WhosWho_Megee/> He was then stationed with the 10th Marines at Quantico, Virginia. He was promoted to first lieutenant in March 1926. In April 1927 Megee deployed to China on his second tour of expeditionary duty. On return to the States in March 1928, he was assigned to preliminary aviation training at the Naval Air Station, San Diego, California. In January 1929 he began another tour of expeditionary service as Squadrons Quartermaster, Aircraft Squadrons, 2nd Marine Brigade, in Nicaragua.<ref name=MCG_Ulbrich_200611>{{cite journal|accessdate=March 6, 2009\n|url=http://www.marinecorpsgazette-digital.com/marinecorpsgazette-share/200611/?pg=76\n|journal=[[Marine Corps Gazette]] |date=November 2006\n|title=Revisiting Small Wars: A 1933 questionnaire, Vernon E. Megee, and the ''Small Wars Manual'' \n|first=David J. |last=Ulbrich}}</ref> After earning the [[Navy and Marine Corps Medal]] there, he returned to the United States to enter flight training at Pensacola, Florida in January 1931.\n\n===Marine aviator \u2014 1930s===\nIn February 1932 he qualified as a [[naval aviator]],<ref name=WhosWho_Megee/> and was assigned to Aircraft Squadrons, West Coast Expeditionary Forces in San Diego, California. From June 1933 to August 1936, he was an instructor at the Marine Corps School in [[Marine Corps Base Quantico|Quantico]], Virginia.<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/> From the period of August 1936 to June 1939, he attended the Air Corps Tactical School at Maxwell Field in Alabama, after which he returned to Quantico as an instructor until July 1939.<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/> From July 1939 until 1940, he was Commander of Marine Fighter Squadron 2, [[2nd Marine Aircraft Wing]].  From 1940 to 1943, Megee was the [[Executive officer#United States|executive officer]] of the U.S. Naval Aviation Mission to [[Peru]].<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/>\n\n===World War II; 1940s===\nIn November 1943, Megee checked into [[Marine Corps Air Station Cherry Point]] and was designated as the Chief of Staff of the [[3rd Marine Aircraft Wing]] (3d MAW). At the time 3d MAW was in charge of pilot training.<ref name=Megee_p103>{{harvnb|Megee|2011|p=103}}</ref>  In the spring of 1944, 3d MAW was designated to go to Hawaii to absorb the functions of Marine Air, Hawaiian Area. Megee left the United States in late April on board the {{USS|Hoggatt Bay|CVE-75}}.<ref name=Megee_p107>{{harvnb|Megee|2011|p=107}}</ref> He remained with the 3d Marine Aircraft Wing as they got established at [[Marine Corps Air Station Ewa]] in May 1944. In October 1944, Colonel Magee was named as the commanding officer of Provisional Air Support Command whose role was to organize, train and equip Marine units to duplicate the air control function of the navy but do it ashore.<ref name=Megee_p110>{{harvnb|Megee|2011|p=110}}</ref> He served in combat in World War II on Iwo Jima and Okinawa. During the [[Battle of Iwo Jima]], he was commander of Landing Force Air Support Control Unit One. For his service in this capacity, he was awarded the [[Legion of Merit]] with Combat \"V\".<ref name=WhosWho_Megee>\"[[#WhosWho|General Vernon E. Megee, USMC]]\", ''Who's Who in Marine Corps History''.</ref>  During  the [[Battle of Okinawa]], he commanded all the Marine Landing Force Air Support Control units, for which he was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]] with Combat \"V\".<ref name=WhosWho_Megee/>\n\n===1950s \u2014 Commands, Assistant Commandant===\n[[File:Marine Corps Birthday Celebration, Korea, 1953 (15533124739).jpg|right|thumb|Megee during the 1953 [[United States Marine Corps birthday|Marine Corps Birthday]] in Korea.]]\nAfter the war, he became an instructor at the [[National War College]], and was promoted to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] in December 1946. From January 1947 to January 1950, he served as assistant director of Marine Corps Aviation.<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/>\n\nMegee finished his [[bachelor's degree]] with Oklahoma A&M in 1950, and then served in a variety of positions in the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] and held several commands: [[Marine Corps Air Station, Cherry Point]] Commanding General, Aircraft, [[Fleet Marine Force, Pacific]], [[First Marine Aircraft Wing]], and commanding general, Aircraft, [[Fleet Marine Force, Atlantic]]. He commanded the 1st Marine Aircraft Wing during the [[Korean War]] from January to December, 1953. He was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] for his service during this time.<ref name=MCLM/><ref>http://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=42339</ref>\n\nHe was promoted to lieutenant general in January 1956. From January 1956 to December 1957, he was [[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps|Assistant Commandant]] and Chief of Staff of the Marine Corps.,<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/> the first Marine aviator to serve as assistant commandant.<ref name=NYT_Lambert_19920119>[[#LambertNYT|Lambert]], ''New York Times'', 1992.</ref> Then from December 1957 to November 1959, he was the commanding general of the Fleet Marine Force, Pacific.<ref name=PapersEisenhower_Chronology/>\n\nMegee retired from the Marine Corps in November 1959 and was advanced to the rank of general upon retirement by reason of having been specially commended in combat.<ref name=WhosWho_Megee/>\n\n===In retirement===\nAfter retirement, he settled in [[Austin, Texas]], and attended graduate school at the [[University of Texas]], earning his [[Master of Arts]] degree in 1963 \u2013 writing a Master's thesis titled \"United States Military Intervention in Nicaragua, 1902\u20131932.\"<ref name=MCG_Ulbrich_200611/> He helped organize the [[Marine Military Academy]] at [[Harlingen, Texas]], where he served as superintendent and president of the board of trustees from 1964 to 1988. He was a member of the [[National Rifle Association]] and wrote numerous articles on firearms for various sporting magazines.\n\nMegee died in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], on January 14, 1992, at age 91 and was buried with [[military funeral|full military honors]] in [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref name=ANC>\"[[#ANC|Vernon E. Megee, General, USMC]]\", ArlingtonCemetery.net.</ref>\n\n==Awards and decorations==\nMegee's awards and decorations include: <center>\n{|\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[File:Naval Aviator Badge.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg |width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|other_device=nv|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|other_device=nv|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Marine Corps Good Conduct ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Marine Corps Expeditionary ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Nicaraguan Campaign ribbon 1933.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Yangtze Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=American Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=American Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon